            <Title>Convention</Title>
            <Text>Marcus leaned heavily on his cane as he waited for the approaching bus, taking some of the weight off his weaker leg after a long day walking around the convention. His plan for the evening was to grab a bite to eat, head back to his hotel room, play a game for a bit on his laptop to unwind, and get some sleep before the last day of the Con. 
He smiled, half-amused, as he watched a group of Imperial Stormtroopers and Star Trek Red-shirts stage a picture of mock combat in front of the convention center. He caught a glimpse of himself in the plexiglass of the bus stop. For a man who just turned 48, and a bit of a nerd at heart, he didn’t look too bad. He was tall, broad shouldered with a good blue collar physique; the sort of guy who looked like he took care of himself without going overboard with it. His short, shiny black hair was spattered with silver and flowed back in a well groomed high fade. His mustache and goatee, also liberally streaked with silver, worked well to soften some of the sharper planes of his face and made his Roman nose seem a bit less prominent. Combined with his cargo shorts, boots, gaming tee, and his goth-y, patch-covered, black denim vest with deep inside pockets, he didn’t look at all out of place. Just one more Gen-X gamer at a Con. 
Glancing around as the back of his neck tingled ever so slightly, Marcus grimaced. He was never completely comfortable in crowds, but it was one of the biggest gaming Cons in the country and a great excuse for visiting Las Vegas in April. He’d just needed to get away for a while to clear his head and relax. A week at a Luxury Vegas Hotel topped off with the Con before he went back to North Carolina was a helluva good way to celebrate his birthday. Of course, his business partner had made a crack about it being a waste of a good midlife crisis, but at least he hadn’t dropped a year’s salary on a sports car like Craig had. Spending that kind of money on that kind of conspicuous consumption just seemed wasteful.
Sighing with relief as heard the city bus turn up [the block from him], Marcus straightened back up, ignoring the low throb from his bum knee, and got in line to board the bus. He found himself stuck standing, but at least it wasn’t a long ride to his hotel and he’d make it in plenty of time for his dinner reservation. The person he really felt bad for was the guy in the Wookie costume a few people ahead of him. It’d been sunny and 90 degrees today, and air conditioning could only do so much in a crowded convention center. He honestly didn’t know how the hardcore cosplay crowd managed it, but couldn’t help admiring their dedication to the craft. 
Marcus grimaced as the bus turned onto the strip, the swaying of the vehicle shifting more of his weight onto his left leg, [the one that had never fully recovered from the injury that ended his military career]. While pain had been a constant companion for the last 25 years, the time he’d spent on his feet today had pushed his tolerance to the limit. He’d need to add soaking in a hot bath to his plans for the evening. 
As the bus trundled toward the main strip, the crowd began to thin, and Marcus finally folded onto a seat with a sigh of relief. He massaged his aching leg, working to loosen up the tight muscles in his thigh.
“Not a style choice then?” a cheerful young lady’s voice asked from the row behind him.
Marcus turned to see a pretty girl, probably less than half his age, smiling down at him, dressed as what he could only assume to be an anime character. She’d clearly noticed the Con badge around his neck and felt comfortable talking to a fellow nerd. He grinned wryly as he answered, “Sadly not so much, I managed to break my legs quite badly in my younger days and the cane has been a necessity ever since.” 
“Wow. That must’ve been quite some break, how’d you do it?”
“Jumping out of an airplane,” his grin became much broader at the surprise on her face. “I landed… poorly.”
“Ouch,” she winced sympathetically, before offering Marcus her hand. “I’m Cassie.”
He gave her a hand a gentlemanly shake, “Marcus. You just in town for the Con or are you local?”
“Local, actually. How about you?”
“Oh, I’m just visiting. This trip is my birthday present to myself, I head back out the day after the Con ends.”
She gave him a sly look, “What a shame, you seem like you’d be fun to get to know.” 
Marcus was taken aback for a moment. Was she flirting with him? Or was he entirely misreading the situation. They’d barely spoken, and she was clearly so much younger than he was, but that mischievous expression left him off balance.
“Uh, thanks,” he stammered, uncertain of how to respond. 
“Oh wow,” her grin turned a little more lascivious, “and shy too. Definitely too bad we didn’t run into each other sooner.”
“Uh, yeah,” he could feel his face heating up, “definitely.” Marcus noticed with an odd feeling of relief that his stop was next. “Maybe we’ll meet again another time under… less constrained circumstances.” He had no problem admitting to himself that he was running away. He just wasn’t sure how to handle aggressive women who were barely older than his own daughter.
</Text>
