            <Title>Bad Business</Title>
            <Text>Marcus smiled and stretched a bit as he stood up. Dinner had been excellent, well worth both the time and money spent. [After a couple of beers with the meal], he felt relaxed and refreshed as he made his way toward the closest elevator. That feeling lasted right up until Dennis Leary began singing ‘I’m an asshole’ from the phone in his pocket, which tossed his relaxation out the window. He only had one person who’d been set to that ring tone for his trip, and he was sure that he would not enjoy this phone call.
Fishing out his phone, he injected forced cheerfulness into his deep baritone, “Craig, this better be an actual, honest to god emergency or I’m going to key your Porsche when I get back.”
“Damn it, Marcus, that’s not funny! When were you going to tell me that Jimmy offered to buy you out? I thought we were in this together?” 
“We were. Actually still are since I haven’t made a decision yet one way or the other,” he answered, “but if you try to say you’re surprised I’m considering it then you’ve been lying to yourself. You know damn well that my heart hasn’t been in it for a while now.”
“I thought that was the point of this whole vacation thing?” Craig countered, “You spend a week in Vegas followed by a week on a Cruise ship, you clear your head and get back in the game.”
“Or I spend those two weeks clearing my head and decide that what’s best for the business is selling my half to Jimmy and riding off into the sunset,” Marcus shot back. “Either way it’s win-win for you cause you’ll either get a motivated partner back in two weeks, or a partner who’s transitioning out to let someone who cares take over.”
“Oh, stow that bullshit. You know Jimmy’s dead weight when it comes to dealing with clients. On his best days he’s half the closer you are on your worst days.”
“Then find somebody else to offer me more than Jimmy did,” he retorted. “I’m tired, Craig. The world is turning to shit around us and I’m just done pretending to care about things that have stopped mattering to me. I’ll send you a copy of Jimmy’s offer, but if you or someone else doesn’t make a better offer than it than I’m making no promises. And if you call me again before I get back, I’ll accept Jimmy’s offer on the spot and you can fucking deal with it. I’m done talking about this.”
Marcus hung up the phone and struggled for a brief moment with the urge to fling it across the hotel concourse. He breathed deeply, focusing on letting go of his frustration. Once upon a time, he and Craig had been equally invested in the security consulting group they’d set up, but they’d ultimately had different standards for constituted success. Craig had always wanted more: more money, more clients, more renown. Marcus, on the other hand, had wanted a life. He wanted enough money to live well, but didn’t need to live extravagantly. He didn’t need a Porsche and a McMansion, didn’t need the newest latest best in everything, didn’t need bespoke suits and a millionaire life. 
Of course, Craig’s marriage had ended in divorce specifically because he wasn’t providing those things to his wife, so maybe Marcus could understand some of the drive there. Since the divorce, however, Craig had been impossible. The job had become his entire life and he spent way too much time listening to podcasts and streams from big shot tech-bros and venture capitalist types. Suddenly his business partner thought they both needed to work  12 hour days 6 days a week to turn their enterprise into something “real.” Marcus thought that was overkill. They didn’t need to be the next Amazon or Google or whatever. There was no way their security consulting group was ever going to be a Fortune 500 company. It just wasn’t realistic.
Letting out a final deep breath that totally wasn’t a sigh, Marcus made up his mind. If Craig wanted to take a small, regional company like theirs and make them some giant national or even multinational concern, he could do it without Marcus. He turned back to his phone, typed up a quick email, attached a copy of the offer Jimmy had made for his interest in the group. 
He sent the email and felt a weight lift off his chest, felt himself melt back into a calm state of mind. [It was the right choice, for him and all he needed to worry about was him and his almost adult daughter.] Craig could figure his own shit out.</Text>
