            <Title>Adaptation</Title>
            <Text>Marcus found his head spinning. He could feel his heart hammering in his chest as the adrenaline in his system put his brain into what his ex-wife had always called crisis mode. His emotions seemed to shut off, his breathing deepened, and his rational mind took over. 
He analyzed the situation logically and considered what he had experienced so far, taking stock of it all. The strange screens he’d seen. The obvious and palpable changes to his physical body. The complete lack of pain in his leg for the first time in literal decades. The strange woman standing in front of him. [life or death combat situations back when he was a soldier.] None of it made sense.
Could he be suffering some manner of psychotic break? Possibly. However, so far everything was coherent and he could follow both the information provided by the strange screens and the answers provided by the woman. His ability to think and analyze the data he was being given didn’t appear to be impaired, even if the data itself and resulting conclusions were outrageous by any objective standard. That didn’t fit with the fractured reasoning associated with severe mental breaks, did it?
Likewise, the clarity of his thoughts seemed to contradict the possibility he had been drugged or injured. It didn’t fully discount the possibility of hallucinations from some other cause, but again that seemed increasingly unlikely given his ability to even consider that possibility. His general understanding of hallucination suggested that while hallucinating, it was almost impossible to consider that you might be hallucinating. Also, would a hallucination or delusion be so consistent? That didn’t seem probable.
Was he thinking clearly though? He tested himself, running through a set of mathematical calculations he’d had ingrained in his memory for long distance shooting. He didn’t stumble or stutter over any step of the equations, so he could only conclude he was, indeed, thinking clearly. That left him faced with Occam’s Razor: the simplest explanation that fits the facts is the most probable explanation. Therefore, he should proceed from the assumption that this was really happening until something proved it wasn’t.
He considered the woman’s responses. She gave direct answers to the questions he’d posed, without volunteering additional information or providing context. That was not typical human conversational behavior. At the same time, she had interpreted his initial outburst as a question and responded accordingly, indicating that she was capable of grasping and answering implied questions as well. There were no value statements or emotional emphasis on anything she said, which suggested that she answered with what she perceived to be statements of fact rather than opinion. That at least provided a path to acquire more information.
“You’re my guide? What does that mean?” he asked finally.
“I am a System projection intended to help you navigate the changes brought about by the first phase of System integration and to prepare you for the tutorial,” she answered. “That means I am here to answer relevant questions for you, teach you basic conceptual knowledge about the System and the Multiverse it governs, and help you assess options and select a path forward.”
“I see,” he said as he considered her response. “A System projection? Does that mean you aren’t real? You’re a hologram or something?”
“I am not a hologram, I am a material projection. A physical manifestation of a limited set of System functions intended to interact with sapient beings in universes that are being integrated into the Multiverse.”
“But you aren’t a fully sapient being yourself?”
“No. I am not classed as sapient as the System is not classed as sapient. While I have some ability to reason and communicate like sapient beings, I do not have a sense of my self as an individual. I exist to serve a purpose and when that purpose is fulfilled I cease to be.” She paused for a moment as though thinking. “It would be easiest for you to consider me an automaton.”
“Why do you appear to be the same as me? Physically I mean.”
“To make it more comfortable for you to interact with me.” Her slight smile brushed the edge of the uncanny valley. “Most sapients find it easier to interact with other individuals of the same or similar phenotype.”
Marcus nodded at the explanation. It made sense given how humans could hate each other for differences as small as skin color. “Since you’re here to answer questions, what is the System?”
“The System is the manifestation of a confluence of cosmic laws and an interface to interact with fundamental principles of that confluence,” she replied, taking on an almost flat affect with this answer.
“Can you elaborate? What cosmic laws? What fundamental principles?” he pressed.
“No further elaboration available. Details of the System and it’s underlying laws and principles are irrelevant to you at this time,” the flat affect persisted as she continued, “Relevant knowledge of the System will become available as you progress in the Multiverse.”
That caused Marcus to frown. The System clearly limited information, but on what criteria? Why? He considered trying to rephrase the question and press further, but decided to pursue other inquiries first. “Ok, then what is the Multiverse?” 
“The Multiverse is the set of universes which have evolved sufficient sapient life to be integrated into the System.” Her voice shifted once more, back to a more human, for lack of a better word, affect. 
“How many universes are we talking about?” Marcus wasn’t entirely unfamiliar with some of the multiverse theories of reality, but clearly this wasn’t quite the same thing.
“This integration brings the total number of universes in the System to 20.”
“Only 20? That seems much lower than I expected. Why so few?”
“For the System to integrate a universe, that universe must meet a set of specific criteria. This includes sufficient ambient mana levels in the universe, containing a minimum threshold of universe maturation indicated by the amount of recognizable sapient life contained therein, and a certain degree of cosmological proximity to a universe that is already integrated.” She tilted her head as she regarded him. “While countless universes exist, thus far only 20 universes meet all criteria. This number will increase as each new universe that is fully integrated brings additional candidates into cosmological proximity of the System.”
That made sense… sort of. Clearly the System was spreading from some point of origin in the cosmos. Maybe universes spread out from some central point like galaxies did in their universe? “How long has the System been spreading through the cosmos?”
“Approximately 5 billion local years have elapsed since the System was initiated. System initiation resulted in a waveform that propagated through the cosmos and triggered the processes which resulted in the formation of life in compatible universes.” As she answered, her voice reverted to the flat affect she had used before when asked directly about the System.
Marcus blinked. He vaguely recalled that the Earth itself wasn’t even 5 billion years old yet. And the System was initiated? That implied that it didn’t spontaneously come to exist but was somehow created? “Why was the System initiated?” The question sprang off his tongue before he consciously decided to ask it.
“The System was initiated to ensure that life persists in the Multiverse and to stabilize universes where sapience develops while fostering growth and strengthening individual sapient organisms.”
Interesting. That question seemed to get around the limits on questions about the System. So maybe, “how does the System foster growth and strengthen sapient organisms?”
“The System accomplishes these goals by two means: by promoting and rewarding competition between organisms and by infusing all multicellular life with sufficient mana to make significant growth and development possible. The increased mana levels also stabilize stellar activity and extend biological lifespans.”
That was… a lot to digest. Whatever the System was, it didn’t appear to be bad thing based on these explanations. He did still need some clarifications based on the terminology the system used, “and just what is mana?”
The woman’s affect became animated once more as they moved away from discussions directly related to the System itself. “Mana is the most fundamental form of external energy. It can be manipulated and altered by both the environment and by life itself. As an organism becomes able to store and concentrate more mana within themselves, they become both more powerful and less susceptible to damage and thereby more likely to continue living. Your planet’s culture had numerous similar notions such as chi or qi, ki, vitae, and prana, though none of those fully encapsulate what mana truly is, as those terms primarily focus on more internalized functions of mana.”
She had no sooner finished her explanation when she froze and the screen reappeared in front of Marcus.

